Calorie restriction (CR) slows aging in numerous species. In the yeast 
Saccharomyces cerevisiae, this effect requires Sir2, a conserved NAD+-dependent 
deacetylase. We report that CR reduces nuclear NAD+ levels in vivo. Moreover, 
the activity of Sir2 and its human homologue SIRT1 are not affected by 
physiological alterations in the NAD+:NADH ratio. These data implicate alternate 
